1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:03,636
SPEAKER_00: In Vienna, two maternity wards sat under one hospital roof.

2
00:00:04,397 --> 00:00:06,700
SPEAKER_00: The first clinic was run by doctors and students.

3
00:00:07,602 --> 00:00:09,144
SPEAKER_00: The second was run by midwives.

4
00:00:09,926 --> 00:00:11,087
SPEAKER_00: The patients were similar.

5
00:00:11,868 --> 00:00:13,111
SPEAKER_00: The death rates were not.

6
00:00:14,071 --> 00:00:19,440
SPEAKER_00: By 1846, the first clinic was losing more than one in ten mothers.

7
00:00:19,420 --> 00:00:22,984
SPEAKER_00: Across the same years, the second stayed under 4%.

8
00:00:23,846 --> 00:00:25,989
SPEAKER_00: Semmelweis found the difference in the routine.

9
00:00:26,048 --> 00:00:31,998
SPEAKER_00: Doctors moved from autopsies to childbirth without effective disinfection.

10
00:00:32,819 --> 00:00:35,442
SPEAKER_00: He required chloride of lime hand disinfection.

11
00:00:36,463 --> 00:00:37,384
SPEAKER_00: Mortality fell.

12
00:00:38,447 --> 00:00:41,390
SPEAKER_00: The evidence worked before germ theory could explain why.

13
00:00:41,411 --> 00:00:43,774
SPEAKER_00: That was the problem.

14
00:00:43,753 --> 00:00:48,594
SPEAKER_00: Believing the data meant believing doctors had been carrying death from the dead to the living.

15
00:00:48,634 --> 00:00:53,253
SPEAKER_00: The institution protected its identity longer than it protected the evidence.

16
00:00:54,078 --> 00:00:57,392
SPEAKER_00: Small causes, massive consequences.
